\b Challenge Solution:
\b0 \
This challenge is fairly straight forward, but, if you ask me, all of the emails look suspicious. Let\'92s look at the first email:\

\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picwgoal9240\pichgoal4060 }}
\fs28 \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\
This is an updated version of a very popular email scam (there\'92s a wonderful Vegas show called \'93The Nigerian Spam Scam Scam\'94 about this). That being said, this email is asking for banking information and comes from an unofficial source (even the Facebook link is broken, adding to the lack of \'91official\'92-ness). Do not ever give out banking information. This email is for sure one of the phishing scams. \
\
Let\'92s look at the second email:\

\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picwgoal9240\pichgoal6440 }}
\fs28 \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\
What relative? Where? Did you notice that the Facebook link from the previous email tried to link to the Calndestine-Enforced Facebook page? How much is the ransom? The emailer makes their money with or without us? What does that mean?\
This is very clearly an attempt to get you to respond with banking information. \
\
Let\'92s look at the third email:\

\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picwgoal9220\pichgoal3820 }}
\fs28 \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\
So, let me be clear in saying that I would delete this email. However, the TAMU challenge is obviously trying to demonstrate a point (even though the subject line has some awful spelling issues). This email is not included as one of the phishing scams for the challenge. The link provided actually takes you to a \'93subscription\'94 page for the service. The idea I think they are trying to express here is that, if you are receiving an email from a service you 
\i know
\i0  (and, let\'92s assume you recently purchased something from College Express) it may be safe to press the link within the email. Again, let me reiterate:
\i  I would not.
